spanishExample: Diez menos dos es igual a ocho.
englishTranslation: Ten minus two equals eight.

spanishExample: ¡Llámala antes del fin de semana!
englishTranslation: Call her before the weekend!
vocabIncluded: del: "of the" before a masculine noun
fin de semana: weekend / end of week (idiom)

spanishExample: ¡Sal a las cinco! Casi es el fin de semana.
englishTranslation: Get out at five! It’s almost the weekend.
vocabIncluded: fin de semana: weekend / end of week (idiom)
sal: go out / come out (Salir imperative)

spanishExample: ¡Salga antes de las seis!
englishTranslation: (Formal) Go out before six!
vocabIncluded: salga: go out / come out (Salir formal imperative)

spanishExample: ¡Salgamos! Son solo las diez y parece un buen tiempo para hacerlo.
englishTranslation: Let’s go out! It’s only ten and it seems like a good time to do it.
vocabIncluded: para: "in order", "in order to" before an infinitive
parece: seems, he/she/it seems (Parecer, present, 3rd person)
salgamos: let’s go out (Salir plural imperative)

spanishExample: Aunque salga, no será un gran hecho.
englishTranslation: Even if she goes out, it won’t be a big occurrence.
vocabIncluded: gran: "big"/"grand" when used right before a noun (adjective)
salga: go out, he/she/it go out (Salir, subjunctive, 3rd person)
será: "will be", "he/she/it will be" (Ser, future, 3rd person)

spanishExample: De hecho, nueve más uno es igual a diez.
englishTranslation: In fact, nine plus one equals ten.

spanishExample: El trato fue peor que la espera, así que no los llamaré de nuevo.
englishTranslation: The treatment was worse than the wait, so I won’t call them again.
vocabIncluded: llamaré: will call, I will call (Llamar, future, 1st person)

spanishExample: Es un hecho que siempre te llama antes de las ocho.
englishTranslation: It’s a fact that she always calls you before eight.
vocabIncluded: "que", meaning "that" as a conjunction (even in cases where "that" disappears in English)
llama: calls, he/she/it calls (Llamar, present, 3rd person)

spanishExample: Estamos saliendo ahora y llamaremos a la puerta.
englishTranslation: We’re going out now and we’ll knock on the door.
vocabIncluded: llamar a la puerta: to call/knock on the door (idiom)

spanishExample: Había parecido un trato.
englishTranslation: It had seemed like a deal.
vocabIncluded: había: "had", "he/she/it had" before a participle (Haber, imperfect, 3rd person)

spanishExample: No llamó porque ya había salido.
englishTranslation: He didn’t call because he had already gone out.
vocabIncluded: había: "had", "he/she/it had" before a participle (Haber, imperfect, 3rd person)
llamó: called, he/she/it called (Llamar, preterite, 3rd person)
ya: adverb meaning "anymore", "already", and a variety of other time-related things

spanishExample: No quiero que salgan porque me pareció una mala idea.
englishTranslation: I don’t want them to go out because it looked to me like a bad idea.
vocabIncluded: "que", meaning "that" as a conjunction (even in cases where "that" disappears in English)
me: "me" as an indirect object ("to me", "for me")
pareció: seemed, he/she/it seemed (Parecer, preterite, 3rd person)
salgan: go out, they go out (Salir, subjunctive, 3rd person plural)

spanishExample: No salimos a las nueve, salimos a las siete.
englishTranslation: We didn’t go out at nine, we went out at seven.
vocabIncluded: salimos: went out, we went out (Salir, preterite, 1st person plural)

spanishExample: Nueve menos seis es igual a tres.
englishTranslation: Nine minus six equals three.

spanishExample: Nunca sale de noche porque solo tiene diez años.
englishTranslation: She never leaves at night because she is only ten years old.
vocabIncluded: sale: goes out, he/she/it goes out (Salir, present, 3rd person)
tener X años: to be X years old (idiom)

spanishExample: Nunca salgo antes de las siete.
englishTranslation: I never go out before seven.
vocabIncluded: salgo: go out, I go out (Salir, present, 1st person)

spanishExample: Nunca te llamo porque nunca salimos.
englishTranslation: I never call you because we never go out.
vocabIncluded: llamo: call, I call (Llamar, present, 1st person)
salimos: go out, we go out (Salir, present, 1st person plural)

spanishExample: Ocho más uno es igual a nueve, pero menos cuatro son cuatro.
englishTranslation: Eight plus one equals nine, but minus four is four.

spanishExample: Parecía que tenía nueve años y que se llamaba María.
englishTranslation: It seemed like she was nine years old and her name was María.
vocabIncluded: "que", meaning "that" as a conjunction (even in cases where "that" disappears in English)
llamarse: any use of to call with a reflexive pronoun, changing the meaning to "to be named"
parecía: seemed, he/she/it seemed (Parecer, imperfect, 3rd person)
tener X años: to be X years old (idiom)

spanishExample: Quiere que salga con ellos porque dice que parecen buenas personas.
englishTranslation: She wants me to go out with them because she says they seem like good people.
vocabIncluded: "que", meaning "that" as a conjunction (even in cases where "that" disappears in English)
parecen: seem, they seem (Parecer, present, 3rd person plural)
salga: go out, I go out (Salir, subjunctive, 1st person)

spanishExample: Quizás salgamos si me llaman antes de las dos.
englishTranslation: Maybe we’ll go out if they call me before two.
vocabIncluded: llaman: call, they call (Llamar, present, 3rd person plural)
salgamos: go out, we go out (Salir, subjunctive, 1st person plural)

spanishExample: Salgan o puede parecer que no quieren llamar.
englishTranslation: (Plural) Get out or it might look like you don’t want to call.
vocabIncluded: "que", meaning "that" as a conjunction (even in cases where "that" disappears in English)
salgan: go out / come out (Salir plural imperative)

spanishExample: Salí antes de las ocho, de hecho, fue a las cuatro.
englishTranslation: I went out before eight; in fact, it was at four.
vocabIncluded: salí: went out, I went out (Salir, preterite, 1st person)

spanishExample: Salió antes de las cinco.
englishTranslation: She went out before five.
vocabIncluded: salió: went out, he/she/it went out (Salir, preterite, 3rd person)

spanishExample: Si no la llamas antes de las diez, saldrá con alguien más.
englishTranslation: If you don’t call her before ten, she’ll go out with someone else.
vocabIncluded: llamas: call, you call (Llamar, present, 2nd person)
saldrá: will go out, he/she/it will will go out (Salir, future, 3rd person)

spanishExample: Si quieres salir, tienes que tener control.
englishTranslation: If you want to go out, you have to have control.
vocabIncluded: using Tener with "que" to indicate obligation

spanishExample: Si sales ahora, puedes ir con ella porque está a la espera.
englishTranslation: If you go out now, you can go with her because she is in waiting.
vocabIncluded: sales: go out, you go out (Salir, present, 2nd person)

spanishExample: Siempre salen de fiesta el fin de semana.
englishTranslation: They always go out partying on the weekend.
vocabIncluded: Salir de fiesta: to go out partying (idiom)
fin de semana: weekend / end of week (idiom)
salen: go out, they go out (Salir, present, 3rd person plural)
